  "prompt": "What are those lines called that are used instead of parenthesis?",
  "response": "The lines used instead of parentheses are called \"dashes.\" There are different types of dashes, with the most common being the em dash (\u2014) and the en dash (\u2013). The em dash is often used to create a strong break in a sentence or to set off information, similar to parentheses. For example: \"She was going to the store\u2014assuming it was still open\u2014before dinner.\" The en dash is typically used to indicate a range of values or to connect related concepts, such as \"the Paris\u2013London flight.\"",
